date: 2010-03-23 02:27:21
---

An example of DOS line-endings follows:
![7374225004_8feea046db](http://ootput.files.wordpress.com/2010/03/7374225004_8feea046db.jpg)
(note the `^M`)

To convert DOS line endings to Unix without the aid of `dos2unix`, in Vim:`
:%s/^M//g`

(use `ctrl-v` `ctrl-m` to input the `^M`.)

Alternatively, to force Vim to use DOS line endings:`
:set ff=dos`